The difference between a Shared Kernel and a SharedModule is discipline. HereвҖҷs how to maintain it.

In the Bounded Contexts article, we introduced the Shared Kernel as a small, curated set of concepts shared identically across all contexts. We said it wasnвҖҷt a dumping ground.
After a few months on a real project, that principle gets tested.
A developer needs Money in checkout вҖ” so it goes to shared-kernel. Someone needs a product status pipe, and it's faster to put it in shared than figure out where it belongs. Then a modal component. Then a UserService. Then a CartHelper that "everyone needs."
Sound familiar? YouвҖҷve just rebuilt the SharedModule problem with a new name.
The Shared Kernel has to be actively defended. This article gives you the rules, the tests, and the tooling to keep it from growing into the thing it was meant to replace.

The Four Tests
A concept earns its place in the Shared Kernel only if it passes all four:
Test 1: Identical semantics everywhere. Money in Cart means exactly the same thing as Money in Checkout and Orders. No context-specific behavior. Compare with Product вҖ” which means something different in every context and rightly lives in each one separately.
Test 2: No context-specific extensions. If any context needs to subclass or extend it for local behavior, it doesnвҖҷt belong here. A Shared Kernel type is used as-is, or not at all.
Test 3: Changing it requires coordinating all contexts. This is the DDD definition. The Shared Kernel is a deliberate coupling вҖ” justified only because the concept is genuinely universal. If a change only affects one context, it belongs in that context.
Test 4: Zero dependencies on any bounded context. The Shared Kernel imports nothing from Catalog, Cart, Checkout, or any other context. It is depended upon вҖ” it never depends.

What Actually Belongs There
After running ShopFlowвҖҷs shared concepts through the four tests:
shared-kernel/
в”ңв”Җв”Җ value-objects/
в”Ӯ в”ңв”Җв”Җ money.value-object.ts вң… Identical meaning everywhere
в”Ӯ в”ңв”Җв”Җ email.value-object.ts вң… Used in Profile, Auth, Checkout
в”Ӯ в”ңв”Җв”Җ address.value-object.ts вң… Checkout, Orders, Profile вҖ” same meaning
в”Ӯ в”ңв”Җв”Җ date-range.value-object.ts вң… Coupons, promotions, shipment windows
в”Ӯ в””в”Җв”Җ ids/
в”Ӯ в”ңв”Җв”Җ typed-id.base.ts
в”Ӯ в”ңв”Җв”Җ product-id.ts
в”Ӯ в”ңв”Җв”Җ cart-id.ts
в”Ӯ в”ңв”Җв”Җ order-id.ts
в”Ӯ в”ңв”Җв”Җ customer-id.ts
в”Ӯ в””в”Җв”Җ cart-item-id.ts
в”ңв”Җв”Җ errors/
в”Ӯ в”ңв”Җв”Җ domain-error.ts вң… Base class вҖ” all contexts use it
в”Ӯ в”ңв”Җв”Җ application-error.ts вң… Base class
в”Ӯ в””в”Җв”Җ http-error.mapper.ts вң… Shared translation logic
в”ңв”Җв”Җ result.ts вң… Used by all domain operations
в”ңв”Җв”Җ entity.base.ts вң… Extended by all entities
в”ңв”Җв”Җ domain-event-bus.ts вң… Cross-context infrastructure
в””в”Җв”Җ index.ts вҶҗ Public APIAnd what does not belong:
shared-kernel/
в”ңв”Җв”Җ product-card.component.ts вқҢ Catalog context
в”ңв”Җв”Җ order-summary.component.ts вқҢ Orders context
в”ңв”Җв”Җ cart.service.ts вқҢ Cart context
в”ңв”Җв”Җ product.model.ts вқҢ Catalog context
в”ңв”Җв”Җ order-status.pipe.ts вқҢ Orders context
в””в”Җв”Җ format-price.ts вқҢ Should be Money.format()That last entry is worth calling out. If format-price.ts exists because Money.format() didn't, the right fix is to add Money.format() вҖ” not to add a utility function to the shared folder.

The ID System: The Legitimate Cross-Context Bridge
IDs are the most naturally shared concept in ShopFlow. The Catalog creates ProductId. The Cart stores ProductId references. Orders stores ProductId references. The ID travels across contexts вҖ” the entity it identifies stays in its own context.
// shared-kernel/value-objects/ids/typed-id.base.ts
export abstract class TypedId {
readonly #value: string; // True private field
protected constructor(value: string) {
const trimmed = value?.trim();
if (!trimmed || trimmed.length === 0) {
throw new Error(`${this.constructor.name} cannot be empty`);
}
if (trimmed.length > 128) {
throw new Error(`${this.constructor.name} exceeds 128 character maximum`);
}
this.#value = trimmed;
}
get value(): string { return this.#value; }
equals(other: this): boolean { return this.#value === other.#value; }
toString(): string { return this.#value; }
toJSON(): string { return this.#value; }
}// Each domain concept gets its own ID class with a factory method
export class ProductId extends TypedId {
static generate(): ProductId { return new ProductId(crypto.randomUUID()); }
static from(v: string): ProductId { return new ProductId(v); }
}export class CartId extends TypedId { static generate() { return new CartId(crypto.randomUUID()); } }
export class OrderId extends TypedId { static generate() { return new OrderId(crypto.randomUUID()); } }
export class CustomerId extends TypedId { static generate() { return new CustomerId(crypto.randomUUID()); } }
export class CartItemId extends TypedId { static generate() { return new CartItemId(crypto.randomUUID()); } }

Address вҖ” A Multi-Context Value Object
Address appears in three ShopFlow contexts with the same meaning in all of them: a physical location with street, city, postcode, and country. It passes all four tests вҖ” which is why it belongs in the Shared Kernel.
// shared-kernel/value-objects/address.value-object.ts
export type CountryCode = 'DE' | 'AT' | 'CH' | 'FR' | 'GB' | 'US' | 'NL' | 'BE';
const COUNTRY_NAMES: Record<CountryCode, string> = {
DE: 'Germany', AT: 'Austria', CH: 'Switzerland',
FR: 'France', GB: 'United Kingdom', US: 'United States',
NL: 'Netherlands', BE: 'Belgium',
};
export class Address {
readonly line1: string;
readonly line2: string | undefined;
readonly city: string;
readonly postcode: string;
readonly countryCode: CountryCode;
readonly state: string | undefined;
constructor(props: {
line1: string; line2?: string; city: string;
postcode: string; countryCode: CountryCode; state?: string;
}) {
if (!props.line1?.trim()) throw new Error('Address line 1 is required');
if (!props.city?.trim()) throw new Error('City is required');
if (!props.postcode?.trim()) throw new Error('Postcode is required');
if (!COUNTRY_NAMES[props.countryCode]) {
throw new Error(`Unsupported country: ${props.countryCode}`);
}
if (props.countryCode === 'US' && !props.state?.trim()) {
throw new Error('State is required for US addresses');
}
this.line1 = props.line1.trim();
this.line2 = props.line2?.trim() || undefined;
this.city = props.city.trim();
this.postcode = this.normalizePostcode(props.postcode, props.countryCode);
this.countryCode = props.countryCode;
this.state = props.state?.trim() || undefined;
}
get countryName(): string { return COUNTRY_NAMES[this.countryCode]; }
format(style: 'inline' | 'multiline' = 'multiline'): string {
const parts = [
this.line1, this.line2, this.city,
this.state, this.postcode, this.countryName
].filter(Boolean) as string[];
return style === 'inline' ? parts.join(', ') : parts.join('\n');
}
// Immutable update - returns a new Address
with(changes: Partial<ConstructorParameters<typeof Address>[0]>): Address {
return new Address({
line1: this.line1, line2: this.line2, city: this.city,
postcode: this.postcode, countryCode: this.countryCode,
state: this.state, ...changes
});
}
equals(other: Address): boolean {
return this.line1 === other.line1 && this.line2 === other.line2 &&
this.city === other.city && this.postcode === other.postcode &&
this.countryCode === other.countryCode && this.state === other.state;
}
private normalizePostcode(postcode: string, country: CountryCode): string {
const cleaned = postcode.trim().toUpperCase().replace(/\s+/g, ' ');
// UK postcodes need a space: "SW1A1AA" вҶ’ "SW1A 1AA"
if (country === 'GB') {
return cleaned.replace(/^([A-Z]{1,2}\d{1,2}[A-Z]?)(\d[A-Z]{2})$/, '$1 $2');
}
return cleaned;
}
}
DateRange вҖ” Another Legitimate Shared Concept
Coupons have validity periods. Promotions have start and end dates. Shipment windows are date ranges. Same concept, same meaning, used across multiple contexts.
// shared-kernel/value-objects/date-range.value-object.ts
export class DateRange {
readonly start: Date;
readonly end: Date;
constructor(start: Date, end: Date) {
if (start >= end) {
throw new Error(
`Start must be before end: ${start.toISOString()} вҖ“ ${end.toISOString()}`
);
}
this.start = new Date(start);
this.end = new Date(end);
}
get durationInDays(): number {
return Math.ceil((this.end.getTime() - this.start.getTime()) / 86_400_000);
}
contains(date: Date): boolean { return date >= this.start && date <= this.end; }
get isActive(): boolean { return this.contains(new Date()); }
get isExpired(): boolean { return new Date() > this.end; }
get isUpcoming(): boolean { return new Date() < this.start; }
overlaps(other: DateRange): boolean {
return this.start < other.end && this.end > other.start;
}
equals(other: DateRange): boolean {
return this.start.getTime() === other.start.getTime() &&
this.end.getTime() === other.end.getTime();
}
}
The Public API: index.ts
The barrel file is the contract. Only what appears here is accessible to other contexts:
// shared-kernel/index.ts
// Value Objects
export { Money } from './value-objects/money.value-object';
export type { CurrencyCode } from './value-objects/money.value-object';
export { Email } from './value-objects/email.value-object';
export { Address } from './value-objects/address.value-object';
export type { CountryCode } from './value-objects/address.value-object';
export { DateRange } from './value-objects/date-range.value-object';
// IDs
export { ProductId, CartId, CartItemId, OrderId, CustomerId }
from './value-objects/ids';
// Base classes
export { Entity } from './entity.base';
export { TypedId } from './value-objects/ids/typed-id.base';
// Error hierarchy
export { DomainError } from './errors/domain-error';
export { ApplicationError } from './errors/application-error';
export { HttpErrorMapper } from './errors/http-error.mapper';
// Result type
export { Result } from './result';
// Infrastructure
export { DomainEventBus } from './domain-event-bus';
export type { DomainEvent } from './domain-event-bus';Anything not listed here doesnвҖҷt exist as far as the rest of the application is concerned.

Domain Kernel vs. UI Library вҖ” Keep Them Separate
The Shared Kernel contains two distinct categories that often get conflated:
Domain Shared Kernel вҖ” framework-agnostic domain concepts. Money, Address, ProductId, DomainError. These could run in a Node.js service or a React app. No Angular dependency required.
UI Component Library вҖ” generic Angular presentational components. ButtonComponent, ModalComponent, MoneyFormatPipe. No domain knowledge. Pure display.
Keep them in separate directories вҖ” ideally separate Nx libraries:
libs/
shared-kernel/ вҶҗ Domain concepts only
value-objects/
errors/
entity.base.ts
result.ts
design-system/ вҶҗ UI primitives, no domain knowledge
components/
button/
input/
modal/
pipes/
money-format.pipe.tsThe confusion between these two categories is usually how product-card.component.ts ends up in the shared kernel. A product card knows about products вҖ” it belongs in the Catalog context. A button knows about nothing вҖ” it belongs in the design system.

Governance: Keeping the Kernel Small
Two practical rules that prevent the Shared Kernel from becoming the next SharedModule:
The Three Contexts Rule вҖ” a concept moves to the Shared Kernel only when at least three different bounded contexts need it with identical semantics. Before that threshold, keep it in the first context that needs it and export it explicitly from that contextвҖҷs barrel file.
The No Extensions Rule вҖ” if any context needs to extend or specialize a Shared Kernel type for local purposes, it doesnвҖҷt belong in the Shared Kernel. Context-specific needs stay in their context.
